    "narrative": "Today\u2019s lineup for **Ghost Ride the WHIP** pivots heavily on targeting poor efficiency from opposing starters to manufacture offensive production, particularly in the stolen base category. **Mickey Moniak** leads the squad with a 75.75 efficiency score; he is our premier play, benefiting from a favorable matchup against Randy V\u00e1squez (xERA 5.43) and a promotion to the #3 spot in the order. Similarly, **Jose Caballero** (72.91) is a high-upside start today. Despite hitting #8, his aggressive base-running profile against a slower delivery from Springs gives him a significant boost in our scarcest category, SB, making him a must-start despite the lower spot in the order. **Giancarlo Stanton** also provides a high floor (68.81) as he leverages his platoon-neutral profile and a healthy 14% skill edge against Springs to anchor the middle of our production.\n\nWhile we are optimized for today, we must navigate several volatile situations. **Corbin Carroll** (56.89) remains a start despite facing the elite Nolan McLean (xERA 3.04). While his raw projection is stifled by the pitcher's quality, his elite sprint speed and elevated xwOBA provide the necessary cushion to keep him in the outfield. Conversely, **Vinnie Pasquantino** (53.94) is an intriguing start; while his raw numbers take a hit against the lefty Anthony Kay, the wind conditions are forecasted to favor his profile, pushing him into the active lineup. We continue to monitor the status of **Gabriel Moreno** and **Corbin Carroll**, as their inclusion relies on pending lineup cards; should they be shuffled down the order or rested, we have depth ready to plug in.\n\nRegarding our bench, **Zach McKinstry** (48.81) represents our \"marginal\" threshold. He narrowly made the cut over our other bench options due to the lack of viable alternatives, but he remains the first candidate to be subbed out if **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Josh Naylor**, **James Wood**, or **Austin Riley** were suddenly activated or cleared for pinch-hitting duties. With a bench currently crowded by players on rest or IL, we are keeping a close watch on **Seiya Suzuki**, **Trevor Story**, and **Brice Turang** to see if their platoon splits improve for tomorrow\u2019s slate. For now, the roster relies on the high-contact approach of **Tyler Soderstrom** and the defensive stability of **Max Muncy** to keep our WHIP and batting average efficient while we chase the counting stats. Prospects like **Dalton Rushing**, **Alex Freeland**, **Carson Williams**, **Gabriel Arias**, and **Travis Bazzana** remain on high-alert standby in our minor league reserve as we assess their readiness for a call-up.",
